A list is a generic ordered collection of elements.
+ There are two types of lists in Kotlin, immutable list and mutable list
    - immutable or read-only lists are created using listOf()
    - mutable lists are created using mutableListOf()
=> In order to access the elements of Kotlin list we can:
    + indexing: listname[index]
    + get: listname.get(index)
    + indexOf: listname.indexOf(element)
        - this will return the index of the first occurring specified element
    + lastIndexOf: listname.lastIndexOf(element)
        - this will return the index of the last occurring specified element
    + lastIndex: listname.lastIndex
        - this will return the last index of the list
    + first: listname.first()
        - this will return the first element of the list
    + last: listname.last()
        - this will return the last element of the list

=> In order to iterate through a list we can:
    + for loop
    + for until loop
    + forEach loop
    + listIterator

=> In order to get the length of the list we using listname.size
=> we use sorted() to sort the list in ascending order, and sortedDescending() to do the opposite
=> we using contains() to check if the list contains a particular element, and containsAll() to check if the list
contains the multiple specified elements